Lt Col Smeltz commands AFMC’s largest Comm Sq, 300+ personnel, and trains/deploys cyber ops Airman supporting the largest AEF commitment of any base-level Comm SQ in AFMC. He manages a $5M annual budget in support of a 23,000 person military community comprised of Air Armament Center, 53d Wing, 33d Fighter Wing, 46th Test Wing, 96th Air Base Wing, 919th Special Operations Wing, 308th Armament Sys Wing, and over 45 associate units. He directs ops/mx on $1.5B C4ISR infrastructure; maintains 169 Antenna Systems; 1.8 Million pair miles of fiber optic and copper cable; telephone switch that processes 145,000 – 160,000 calls per day and provides other IT services on base
name: Stamatis Smeltz

title: VP DoD Programs
description: Lead a business unit (50+ people) focused on a full spectrum of program management support. Specialties include customized training on Army's General Fund Enterprise Business System (GFEBS), on site support for GFEBS and legacy financial systems, and specialized DPW workload/financial management support. Supported customers include strategic level (ASA (FM&C)) to multiple tactical level customers (DPWs, Project Offices and Directorates).
name: Richard Manley

title: Chief, Enterprise Integration Center
description: Led a diverse team of 200 technical specialists, logistics SMEs and program support staff in development, fielding, sustainment, and data center operations for the Logistics Information Warehouse (LIW). •Product Development Led the effort to integrate two large legacy logistics databases into the LIW, thus achieving a Secretary of Army mandate to create a single, authoritative repository for logistics data. This was accomplished on schedule and on budget. Personally led the technical development of custom software tools such as the Automated RESET Management Tooland Theater Provided Equipment Planner, which directly contributed to the management of Army materiel in Southwest Asia and enabled equipment withdrawal from Iraq. Delivered an automated decision support tool which enabled redistribution of all Army equipment. This product was developed to meet a directive by Secretary of Army to allow AMC to assume the role of Lead Materiel Integrator for all Army equipment. •Data Center Operation Developed and implemented the vision of acquiring complex data center capabilities as service. This approach created state of the art computing capability while avoiding capital investment costs. •Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) Managed the creation of a unique data cleansing and master data management capability supporting all instances of the Army’s ERP strategy. Proposed and implemented a strategy for Common Storage Area Network supporting LOGSA and the Army’s ERP resulting in a significant cost savings while enhancing technical capabilities for the ERPs. Led a technical and functional team in development of Business Objects capabilities depicting critical supply and maintenance metrics from ERP and non-ERP data sources Financial and Contract Management Successfully managed an operating program valued at $150M. Responsible for successful execution of 50 separate contract delivery orders. Experienced in all phases of acquistion and source selection process.
name: Richard Manley

title: Dep CIO
description: Served as the Business Manger, Automated Information Systems Manager and Deputy Director of the Corporate Information Center, exercising program control over an operating program of approximately $100M. This included management of all phases of PPBES and manpower management. Also, I managed approximately 100 government civilians and 150 contractor employees in the development of automated information systems for use by AMCOM, PMs/PEOs and other customers. These automated systems were written in various programming languages (COBOL, S2K, M204, Empress, FoxPro, ORACLE, etc). Key accomplishments include the movement of over 100 bridge and unique programs from US Army Aviation and Troop Command in St Louis to the newly formed US Army Aviation and Missile Command at Redstone Arsenal, AL.
name: Richard Manley

title: Director Pol-Mil Affairs (Africa)
company: Strategic Plans and Policy (J5), Joint Staff
description: Senior military officer responsible for development of strategy and policy recommendations for all military issues related to 53 countries in Africa. Led a high-quality team of professional mid-career Soldiers, Sailors, Airmen, and Marines to develop policy recommendations for the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and other senior uniformed and civilian leaders. Provided expert military advise and policy recommendations on a wide range of African security challenges to the National Security Council (NSC); and creatively fostered dialog with the NSC staff and interagency on appropriate DOD operations in support of national security objectives. Shaped policy recommendations, in coordination with State Department and other agencies, to ensure the NSC provided executable policy guidance for: DOD responses to potential crises springing from the effort to ensure independence of South Sudan; DoD support of efforts to restore security and establish a stable government and governing institutions in Somalia; and DOD actions in response to the turmoil of multiple overlapping African crises, from operations in Cote d'Ivoire to seat the elected president, Tunisia's ‘Arab Spring’ revolution, Operation Unified Protector in Libya and relations with post-Qaddafhi Libya; and continued support to combined efforts to defeat the Lord’s Resistance Army in Central Africa. Worked cooperatively with State Department to develop support and resourcing for programs focused on Security Sector Reform, peacebuilding, and leadership, with emphasis on DoD roles. Championed an initiative leading to a multilateral strategic approach to resolve the challenges in the Sahel resulting from the emergence of al-Qaeda in Mali.
name: Christopher Leins

title: Deputy Commander
description: Deployed to Djibouti as the deputy commander of a combined military organization of more than 3,000 U.S. and allied personnel with the mission to foster regional security cooperation with 13 nations of East Africa, strengthen their security capacity, and enable leadership development. As the senior U.S. Army officer, I used my knowledge of land force operations to improve the planning and execution of military-to-military training opportunities with our African partners, and to significantly improve the conduct of civil-military operations throughout the Horn of Africa. Developed and nurtured relationships with key senior military leaders in African partner nations, and worked with US interagency partners, including the Department of State and USAID, to facilitate a 'whole of government' approach to achieving US objectives in Africa.

title: Biography
description: Colonel Allen has served at multiple and diverse levels. He reported to Marine Corps Recruiting Command, San Diego in 1985 and was commissioned in 1986. As a Lieutenant, he served as a disbursing officer at a Marine Logistics Group and at a Marine Air Station. As a Captain, he was a regimental personnel officer, an adjutant, and S-1 officer. As a Major, he commanded a Motor Transport Company, and served as an artillery regiment logistics operations officer. As a Lieutenant Colonel, he served in two Divisions as the deputy and assistant G-1; he deployed from 1st Marine Division to Operation Iraqi Freedom and served as an advisor to the Iraq Ministry of Defense M-1 under the Multi-National Security Transition Command – Iraq, Joint Headquarters Assistance Team, and to the Ministry of Interior Transition Team. Upon return to 1st Marine Division, he assumed duties as the deputy G-7, the Inspector General and promoted to Colonel. As a Colonel, he directed the Requirements & Programs of Regional Operations and Plans branch at Marine Forces Command for Marine forces supporting US Northern Command, US Joint Forces Command and US Strategic Command. From Marine Forces Command, Colonel Allen deployed to Afghanistan as the Command Inspector General and Science and Technology Officer of RC(SW) Afghanistan for II Marine Expeditionary Force (Fwd) United States Marine Corps. Currently Colonel Allen will attend Midwestern State University full time to major in both Mathematics and Chemistry as a Pre-Medical student.
name: Col Michael David Allen, DMSM, BA, USMC

title: A Senior Policy Advisor at the Multi-National Security Transition Command Iraq
description: • A Senior Advisor of the Multi-National Security Transition Command for policy making to the Iraqi Ministry of Defense and the Iraqi Ministry of Interior •Requested to assist British Commanding General to Iraqi MOI to develop policy that would influence Iraqi Minister to adopt fairer police hiring policy with 30-day timeline. •Worked directly with Iraqi government policy makers and administrative machinery for effective manpower policy formation to transform Personnel Management into mission-oriented, trained and focused staff section. •Advised Iraqi principal daily on effective, efficient methods in policy development, force structure management, personnel management and accountability. •Defined personnel operations for MOI that achieved higher transparency, controls and consistency in recruiting paramilitary and police forces. •Built structure for sustainment of personnel operations,programming and planning necessary for force generation and sustainment of Army, Navy, Air Force and Special Operations Force. •Developed personnel management policies and information technology to accomplish personnel functions related to rank structure/management, skill/manpower requirement projections, accession mix determinations, force sustainment and force management/accountability for 160K Iraqi Armed Forces. •Partnered with MOD to access to Identification Cards database to determine baseline for personnel strength numbers and force structure data; initiative led to creation of manpower requirements database to manage controls for structure managements and determine future manpower projections. Key Accomplishments: ➢Advised MOD in shaping/influencing senior Iraqi General Officers toward adopting policy proposals to stop internal corruption within senior leadership and staffs: led development of integrated game plan for Iraqi personnel recruiting, training and assignments. ➢Nominated for Bronze Star Medal; awarded Defense Meritorious Service Medal for distinguished actions.
name: Col Michael David Allen, DMSM, BA, USMC

title: 1st Marine Division Assistant G-1 - Senior Leader of Manpower,Reserve Liaisons,Casualty Operations
description: Senior Leader for Personnel Affairs at 1st Marine Division headquarters / 2004-2005 Assistant Manpower Officer/Reserve Liaison Officer/Casualty Operations Center Director Chief Director of Casualty Operations for 1st Marine Division • Directed workforce of 19,000: sourced manpower across globe. • Managed extensive database of more than 35 fields that tracked/maintained accountability of all casualties, providing most updated (and detailed) information: ensured represendation at 1354 funerals displaying commitment and made very positive impression upon families of deceased. • Filled 89% of personnel for key staffing posts: coordinated/planned all laor to estimate future requirements. • Continually sought as “the Go-To” in all manpower related matters: identified candidates, requested orders, conducted interviews, provided housing justification, tracked progress, payroll, and handled order processing. Key Accomplishments: ➢ Rapidly recruited Reserves with specialized civilian skill sets within 2-month period using exceptional high-level coordination actions. ➢ Pivotal figure in completing sourcing and staffing of all individual manpower requirements to provide crucial expertise in areas such as civil affairs, legal issues and intelligence collection. ➢ Directed Casualty Operations Center and coordinated casualty tracking that ensured accurate and actionable combat casualty information was rapidly provided to next of kin with zero errors. ➢ Sought/gained approval to extend orders for 100% personnel to key staffing posts saving thousands of dollars in manpower cost. ➢ Sustained cooperation from 26 medical treatment facilities that ensured most accurate information significantly improving timeliness and accuracy of updated patient information.
name: Col Michael David Allen, DMSM, BA, USMC

title: Biography
description: Colonel Allen has served at multiple and diverse levels. He reported to Marine Corps Recruiting Command, San Diego in 1985 and was commissioned in 1986. As a Lieutenant, he served as a disbursing officer at a Marine Logistics Group and at a Marine Air Station. As a Captain, he was a regimental personnel officer, an adjutant, and S-1 officer. As a Major, he commanded a Motor Transport Company, and served as an artillery regiment logistics operations officer. As a Lieutenant Colonel, he served in two Divisions as the deputy and assistant G-1; he deployed from 1st Marine Division to Operation Iraqi Freedom and served as an advisor to the Iraq Ministry of Defense M-1 under the Multi-National Security Transition Command – Iraq, Joint Headquarters Assistance Team, and to the Ministry of Interior Transition Team. Upon return to 1st Marine Division, he assumed duties as the deputy G-7, the Inspector General and promoted to Colonel. As a Colonel, he directed the Requirements & Programs of Regional Operations and Plans branch at Marine Forces Command for Marine forces supporting US Northern Command, US Joint Forces Command and US Strategic Command. From Marine Forces Command, Colonel Allen deployed to Afghanistan as the Command Inspector General and Science and Technology Officer of RC(SW) Afghanistan for II Marine Expeditionary Force (Fwd) United States Marine Corps. Currently Colonel Allen will attend Midwestern State University full time to major in both Mathematics and Chemistry as a Pre-Medical student.
name: Col Michael David Allen, DMSM, BA, USMC

description: • A Senior Advisor of the Multi-National Security Transition Command for policy making to the Iraqi Ministry of Defense and the Iraqi Ministry of Interior •Requested to assist British Commanding General to Iraqi MOI to develop policy that would influence Iraqi Minister to adopt fairer police hiring policy with 30-day timeline. •Worked directly with Iraqi government policy makers and administrative machinery for effective manpower policy formation to transform Personnel Management into mission-oriented, trained and focused staff section. •Advised Iraqi principal daily on effective, efficient methods in policy development, force structure management, personnel management and accountability. •Defined personnel operations for MOI that achieved higher transparency, controls and consistency in recruiting paramilitary and police forces. •Built structure for sustainment of personnel operations,programming and planning necessary for force generation and sustainment of Army, Navy, Air Force and Special Operations Force. •Developed personnel management policies and information technology to accomplish personnel functions related to rank structure/management, skill/manpower requirement projections, accession mix determinations, force sustainment and force management/accountability for 160K Iraqi Armed Forces. •Partnered with MOD to access to Identification Cards database to determine baseline for personnel strength numbers and force structure data; initiative led to creation of manpower requirements database to manage controls for structure managements and determine future manpower projections. Key Accomplishments: ➢Advised MOD in shaping/influencing senior Iraqi General Officers toward adopting policy proposals to stop internal corruption within senior leadership and staffs: led development of integrated game plan for Iraqi personnel recruiting, training and assignments. ➢Nominated for Bronze Star Medal; awarded Defense Meritorious Service Medal for distinguished actions.
name: Col Michael David Allen, DMSM, BA, USMC

title: Logistics Site Lead
description: - Analyze unit performance during gaming lane training and gaming environment exercises through every phase of each mission. - Provide subject matter expertise involving doctrine, Tactics Techniques and Procedures (TTP), tactical planning, on Improvised Explosive Device (IED) operations to include in-depth advice, counsel and assistance to exercise unit operations personnel before, during and after gaming exercises. - Provide in-depth assessments, oral and written, of unit performance and provide feedback to the unit using the After Action Review (AAR) process at the completion of the exercise. - Coach, mentor, and teach unit IED skills and tasks using current doctrine, techniques and procedures to ensure units are combat ready. - Gather, develop, organize and disseminate information on current enemy and friendly trends, TTPs and operations. - Interface with members of all Observer/Controller teams regarding training of the units, development of rotation scripts, and execution of scripts during rotations, pre-rotational briefings, and after-action meetings and reports. - Develops tests, maintains, and delivers complex training programs in a classified environment, and related materials in support of customer training objectives.
name: Michael Hurd
headquarters: United States
address: United States

title: Senior Military Analyst/Database Management
description: - Design, build, test, and execute Logistical Exercises (LEX) incorporating Joint Deployment Logistics Model (JDLM) simulation to stimulate the Battle Command Support System (BCS3) systems to support Army Logistics University’s learning objectives for the Combined Logistics Captain’s Career Course (CLC3), CLC3-Reserve Component, Warrant Officer Advanced Course, and other logistics courses (such as the Advanced Non-commission Officers Advanced Course) as designated by the government. - Advise the government on changes to the LEX events to meet emerging doctrine and incorporate approved tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) that support ALU’s learning objectives. - Assist small group leaders (SGL), instructors, and students on the employment of BCS3 in the distribution management process and apply distribution management techniques and its relationship to the U.S. Army STAMIS in accordance with ALU learning objectives. - Facilitate final LEX After Action Review (AAR). - Train military, government and selected contractors (those designated and filling Contracted SGL Instructor Positions) on the use of the JDLM Simulation, and BCS3. - Facilitate movement of all required data used to stimulate BCS3 and assist the training audience in the interpretation of the data used to make logistics decisions. - Build logistic parameters, networks; logistics force structure, in transit visibility, strategic and tactical movement capabilities as well as consumption regions and agents to support the requirements of the training audience supporting logistics operations, distribution management and strategic deployment and sustainment operations. - Linkage and train JDLM functionality in exercises and other simulation events where JDLM is linked to JCATS or CBS. - Upgrade system burn-in/testing of new soft ware releases for JDLM stimulation software and BCS3 software.
name: Michael Hurd
headquarters: United States
address: United States

title: Senior Military Analyst
description: - Design, analysis, implementation, test, documentation, operational maintenance, and quality assurance of Marine Corps databases for Joint Deployment Logistics Model (JDLM). - Integrates the Marine Corps Logistics Bridging Technologies (BCS3, CLC2S, TCPT, WTW/LTM and MERIT) and other Marine Corps Command and Control Systems into the MAGTF Logistics Combat Element scenario design. - Conduct simulated exercise development with United States Marine Corps (USMC) Units preparing to deploy. - Interview operational personnel from units participating in the simulated exercises. - Translates real world or fictional enemy and friendly force structures into an exercise simulation database. - Conduct testing on Simulation Stimulation processes for USMC data from JDLM to Battle Command Sustainment Support System (BCS3). - Take guidance drawn from an analysis of customer training objectives and use the JDLM model to emulate the appropriate force structure, infrastructure, and logistics force structure in support of achieving exercise objectives. - Provide support to the mission planning and mission execution processes which may include modeling the strategic deployment process down to individual entity level moves reflecting mobilization, movement and final deployment and Reception, Staging, Onward movement and Integration. - Assist in determining the physical layout, networking and simulation architecture in support of individual exercises, operational exercises, and Joint support events. - Capable of assisting in the design of simulations supported training events, data base design, data base build, and the stimulation of logistics C4I systems such as BCS3. - Translate logistical and operational force structure, simulation training design, exercise objectives and able to understand an operational plan and logistic implications of staff planning. - Translate variables into a viable JDLM scenario.
name: Michael Hurd
headquarters: United States
address: United States

title: Logistics Enlisted Assignment Monitor
description: Manpower and Reserve Affairs, Quantico, VA 2004 to 2008 Logistics Enlisted Assignment Monitor - Hand selected to manage the staffing and assignment of 4000 Marines within the logistics community. - Communicate daily with the Marine and their commands in order to meet the needs of the Marine Corps, the Marine, and the Marines families through emails, telephone calls, and through the Occupational Field Sponsor at supporting establishments. - Resolve strategic concerns with monitored commands through their senior enlisted and officer, and educate them on the process used to staff the Marine Corps. - Make assignments to Monitored Command Codes per guidance of the personnel assignment policy using the Authorized Strength Report and Enlisted Staffing Goal according to the Staffing Precedence Policy. - Coordinate and approve annual training requirements. - Mentor and Counsel Marines as to career progression and professional development. - Endorse requests for reenlistment, retirements, joint household, overseas extensions, special duty assignments, humanitarian transfer, occupational lateral moves, and exceptional family member relocation.

description: Installation and Logistics, Washington, DC 2000 to 2004 Logistics Occupational Manager - Hand selected to act as the Enlisted Installation and Logistics coordinator for the Logistics population. - Reviewed and approved over 115 requests for uncompensated structure. - Approved and disapproved Table of Organization and Table of Equipment for official Installation and Logistics response. - Approved and disapproved all logistical training requirements. - Reviewed all contracts in support of the Logistics Community and made recommendations to approving authorities. - Coordinated the Officer and Enlisted Grade Structure review conducted by Total Force Structure.

title: Command Information Operations (IO) Manager
description: Manages Information Operations (IO) & provides special operations (SO) subject matter expertise (SME) support. Oversees & produce IO Annex's for all assigned Operational Planning Teams (OPTs) in accordance with joint and command policies. Liaison & interface with external agencies in support of IO. Provide SME support, coordination & synchronization in support of external IO plans & operations to inter-agency & other combatant commands utilizing Special Operations Forces (SOF). Develop policy, doctrine, & training on IO for SOF. Ensures integration of IO into all SOF activities, across the enterprise, to improve mission success & reduce risk to forces. Interfaces with Office of the Secretary of Defense (OSD), Joint Staff (JS), & other government agencies on all issues related to IO & SO. Provide adversary & cultural perspectives with regard to friendly plans & operations in supported SO -- globally. Test & challenge assumptions in support of Irregular/Unconventional Warfare & influence planning. Interface with academia & the private sector to increase knowledge of operational environment & cross-cultural communication to facilitate SO & IO. Develop, analyze & report Measures of Performance & Measures of Effectiveness for SOF IO. Manages $12+ Million Annual Budget. Responsible for all PPB&E & POM submissions, contracting, execution & reporting to congressional oversight & OSD. Develops all Integrated Priority List (IPL) submissions for SOF IO. Prepares Unfunded Requirement requests to cover operations requirements not already funded as programs of record. Serves as J3 representative to validate SOFCIDS & JCIDS requirements for IO & Military Deception capabilities. Oversees the execution of SOF IO programs. Evaluates program effectiveness. Designs & implements control & program efficiency measures. Develops reports on performance for HQ, Joint Staff, OSD, & Congressional oversight. Serves as Adjunct Instructor at Joint Special Operations University .
name: Frank Moneymaker

title: Intelligence Operations Division Mission and Resources Manager
description: Served as senior staff officer and divisional intelligence resource manager. Performed manpower/personnel actions as required (260+ active duty, reservists, DoD civilian and contractor personnel). Supported all DoD/Intelligence Community Service and Command taskings to the division. Oversaw programmatic development and execution of division budgets ($40+ million), to include supplemental. Established policies, processes, procedures, and organizations to accomplish the division's mission. Responsible to the director for all performance metrics of the division's operations. Performed as Senior Terrorism Analyst and advised command leadership on all matters pertaining to terrorism worldwide. Served as a terrorism analyst at the expert level in support of USSOCOM's mission for the Global War on Terrorism. Planned, coordinated, collected, and produced multi-faceted intelligence support. Assessed threats, intentions, modus operandi, environment, and developing trends of terrorists, terrorist organizations/networks to include non-governmental organizations and state sponsors of terrorism. Represented the J2 with national intelligence community. Provided expert management of threat analysis, counter terrorism operations, CONPLANs, intelligence production, and collection priorities.

title: Deputy Chief, Intelligence Support to Information Operations Branch
description: Performed intelligence analysis and oversaw production/operations of 33 military and civilian intelligence analysts supporting Special Operations and counter-terrorism Information Operations(IO). Managed $4+ million programs supporting all IO pillars. Served as staff officer writing new plans and synchronizing existing offensive IO plans in support of USSOCOM GWOT efforts. Identified intelligence shortfalls and tasked intelligence community support from all national agencies. Synchronized collection & production requirements across all Unified Combatant Commands to support full spectrum IO, including Special Technical Operations (STO) in support of GWOT. Responsible for USSOCOM's entry point for operational intelligence support to IO, SAP, & STO for GWOT. Prepared flag officer communications and positions to senior DOD officials. Preparesd intelligence support to IO budgets for submission through command channels. Identified funding shortfalls and processed supplemental funding requests. Reviewed organizational manning (active duty, DoD civilian, reservist, & contractor), identified requirements and prepared staff actions for billet creation/assignment. Created intelligence support to IO procedures and programs. Provided quality assurance and review of all analytic products from J239. Provided non-kinetic/IO targeting expertise to J3 and J5.
name: Frank Moneymaker

title: USSOCOM Joint Operations Center Watch Officer
description: Led transitional intelligence production team – Commander (CDR) USSOCOM's sole source for strategic intelligence information. Led USSOCOM Joint Operations Center's (JOC) intelligence force. Produced mission analysis and CDR's assessments for all exercises during time assigned and USSOCOM's Hurricane Katrina response. Supervised DOD civilians and joint military team of intelligence professionals -- officer and enlisted. Responsible for constructing and delivering standing and ad hoc briefings, information papers and other intelligence products to CDRUSSOCOM, CSO Director, staff and distinguished visitors. Supported formulation and execution of critically sensitive, high-risk plans and counter-terrorism operations for the GWOT. Conducted research and analysis on specified terrorist organizations and high-value individuals impacting SOCOM's global AOR. Routinely interfaced and coordinated with counterparts at national agencies and all other combatant commands. Provided time-sensitive intelligence indications and warnings to CDRUSSOCOM and subordinate components/units. Responsible for coordination with national agencies on all CT indications and warnings. Provided tailored analysis on adversary Tactics, Techniques, Procedures and their impacts to Special Operations Forces (SOF) operations...prepared mitigation methods enhancing SOF success and survivability in the CENTCOM AOR. Created systems base-line for intelligence operations in new Warfighter Center JOC. Served as battle captain/operations officer as required.
name: Frank Moneymaker

title: Deputy Chief, Intelligence Applications Branch
description: Oversaw operations of nine-person branch. Integrated targeting, imagery production, and collection management functions in support of Eleventh Air Force (11 AF, corps staff equivalent), Alaskan Command (PACOM), and Alaska NORAD Region missions. Provided target intelligence for range targets and for JTF-519. Supported Air Tasking Order (ATO) development for 11 AF and ALCOM exercises. Lead target production and ensured all Alaska-based forces (Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine) received timely targeting, imagery, and intelligence collection support. Served as 11 AF Foreign Disclosure Officer and unit anti-terrorism officer. Responsible for all targeting, imagery and collection management programs across the command and 4 subordinate wings. Responsible for budgeting, manpower, training and systems acquisition supporting targeting, imagery exploitation and collection management in the Alaskan AOR. Air Force lead for exercise and contingency deployment evaluation of combat forces intelligence capabilities. Chosen as "personal targeteer" by 3-star, responsible for reviewing/approving all kinetic and non-kinetic (IO) targets planned for JTF-519 and war gaming alternatives. Liaison with State Emergency Management to assist in homeland security and consequence management planning. Provided information superiority and planning for joint and combined air campaign planning.

title: USSOCOM Joint Operations Center Watch Officer
description: Led transitional intelligence production team – Commander (CDR) USSOCOM's sole source for strategic intelligence information. Led USSOCOM Joint Operations Center's (JOC) intelligence force. Produced mission analysis and CDR's assessments for all exercises during time assigned and USSOCOM's Hurricane Katrina response. Supervised DOD civilians and joint military team of intelligence professionals -- officer and enlisted. Responsible for constructing and delivering standing and ad hoc briefings, information papers and other intelligence products to CDRUSSOCOM, CSO Director, staff and distinguished visitors. Supported formulation and execution of critically sensitive, high-risk plans and counter-terrorism operations for the GWOT. Conducted research and analysis on specified terrorist organizations and high-value individuals impacting SOCOM's global AOR. Routinely interfaced and coordinated with counterparts at national agencies and all other combatant commands. Provided time-sensitive intelligence indications and warnings to CDRUSSOCOM and subordinate components/units. Responsible for coordination with national agencies on all CT indications and warnings. Provided tailored analysis on adversary Tactics, Techniques, Procedures and their impacts to Special Operations Forces (SOF) operations...prepared mitigation methods enhancing SOF success and survivability in the CENTCOM AOR. Created systems base-line for intelligence operations in new Warfighter Center JOC. Served as battle captain/operations officer as required.
name: Frank Moneymaker

Provided target intelligence for range targets and for JTF-519. Supported Air Tasking Order (ATO) development for 11 AF and ALCOM exercises. title: Command Information Operations (IO) Manager
description: Manages Information Operations (IO) & provides special operations (SO) subject matter expertise (SME) support. Oversees & produce IO Annex's for all assigned Operational Planning Teams (OPTs) in accordance with joint and command policies. Liaison & interface with external agencies in support of IO. Provide SME support, coordination & synchronization in support of external IO plans & operations to inter-agency & other combatant commands utilizing Special Operations Forces (SOF). Develop policy, doctrine, & training on IO for SOF. Ensures integration of IO into all SOF activities, across the enterprise, to improve mission success & reduce risk to forces. Interfaces with Office of the Secretary of Defense (OSD), Joint Staff (JS), & other government agencies on all issues related to IO & SO. Provide adversary & cultural perspectives with regard to friendly plans & operations in supported SO -- globally. Test & challenge assumptions in support of Irregular/Unconventional Warfare & influence planning. Interface with academia & the private sector to increase knowledge of operational environment & cross-cultural communication to facilitate SO & IO. Develop, analyze & report Measures of Performance & Measures of Effectiveness for SOF IO. Manages $12+ Million Annual Budget. Responsible for all PPB&E & POM submissions, contracting, execution & reporting to congressional oversight & OSD. Develops all Integrated Priority List (IPL) submissions for SOF IO. Prepares Unfunded Requirement requests to cover operations requirements not already funded as programs of record. Serves as J3 representative to validate SOFCIDS & JCIDS requirements for IO & Military Deception capabilities. Oversees the execution of SOF IO programs. Evaluates program effectiveness. Designs & implements control & program efficiency measures. Develops reports on performance for HQ, Joint Staff, OSD, & Congressional oversight. Serves as Adjunct Instructor at Joint Special Operations University .
name: Frank Moneymaker

description: Served as senior staff officer and divisional intelligence resource manager. Performed manpower/personnel actions as required (260+ active duty, reservists, DoD civilian and contractor personnel). Supported all DoD/Intelligence Community Service and Command taskings to the division. Oversaw programmatic development and execution of division budgets ($40+ million), to include supplemental. title: USSOCOM Joint Operations Center Watch Officer
description: Led transitional intelligence production team – Commander (CDR) USSOCOM's sole source for strategic intelligence information. Led USSOCOM Joint Operations Center's (JOC) intelligence force. Produced mission analysis and CDR's assessments for all exercises during time assigned and USSOCOM's Hurricane Katrina response. Supervised DOD civilians and joint military team of intelligence professionals -- officer and enlisted. Responsible for constructing and delivering standing and ad hoc briefings, information papers and other intelligence products to CDRUSSOCOM, CSO Director, staff and distinguished visitors. Supported formulation and execution of critically sensitive, high-risk plans and counter-terrorism operations for the GWOT. Conducted research and analysis on specified terrorist organizations and high-value individuals impacting SOCOM's global AOR. Routinely interfaced and coordinated with counterparts at national agencies and all other combatant commands. Provided time-sensitive intelligence indications and warnings to CDRUSSOCOM and subordinate components/units. Responsible for coordination with national agencies on all CT indications and warnings. Provided tailored analysis on adversary Tactics, Techniques, Procedures and their impacts to Special Operations Forces (SOF) operations...prepared mitigation methods enhancing SOF success and survivability in the CENTCOM AOR. Created systems base-line for intelligence operations in new Warfighter Center JOC. Served as battle captain/operations officer as required.
name: Frank Moneymaker

title: Deputy Chief, Intelligence Applications Branch
description: Oversaw operations of nine-person branch. Integrated targeting, imagery production, and collection management functions in support of Eleventh Air Force (11 AF, corps staff equivalent), Alaskan Command (PACOM), and Alaska NORAD Region missions. Provided target intelligence for range targets and for JTF-519. Supported Air Tasking Order (ATO) development for 11 AF and ALCOM exercises. Lead target production and ensured all Alaska-based forces (Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine) received timely targeting, imagery, and intelligence collection support. Served as 11 AF Foreign Disclosure Officer and unit anti-terrorism officer. Responsible for all targeting, imagery and collection management programs across the command and 4 subordinate wings. Responsible for budgeting, manpower, training and systems acquisition supporting targeting, imagery exploitation and collection management in the Alaskan AOR. Air Force lead for exercise and contingency deployment evaluation of combat forces intelligence capabilities. Chosen as "personal targeteer" by 3-star, responsible for reviewing/approving all kinetic and non-kinetic (IO) targets planned for JTF-519 and war gaming alternatives. Liaison with State Emergency Management to assist in homeland security and consequence management planning. Provided information superiority and planning for joint and combined air campaign planning.
